"Lower risk of respiratory depression","Selective delta-opioid receptor binding"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETramadol is distinguished by its \u003Cstrong\u003Eadditional monoamine reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E properties. Unlike pure opioids, tramadol inhibits both serotonin and noradrenaline reuptake while also acting as a weak mu-opioid receptor agonist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater binding affinity for mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Tramadol actually has weaker mu-opioid receptor binding than pure opioids like morphine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELonger duration of action\u003C/strong\u003E - Tramadol\u0027s duration of action is not significantly different from other opioids\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELower risk of respiratory depression\u003C/strong\u003E - While tramadol may have less respiratory depression than some opioids, this is not its key distinguishing feature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective delta-opioid receptor binding\u003C/strong\u003E - Tramadol primarily acts on mu-opioid receptors, not delta receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis dual mechanism of action makes tramadol unique among opioid medications and explains its potential for interactions with both opioid and serotonergic drugs. The parent compound has weak opioid activity but is metabolised to the more potent mu-opioid agonist O-desmethyltramadol.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tramadol is unique among opioids due to its dual mechanism combining weak mu-opioid receptor agonism with monoamine reuptake inhibition.","Unlike pure opioids, tramadol inhibits both serotonin and noradrenaline reuptake.","Tramadol requires metabolism by CYP2D6 to produce its active metabolite O-desmethyltramadol."],"references":["